SIMPLE: litter
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Litter
<hw>Lit"ter</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧t"t⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>liti⟦egrave⟧re</ets>, LL. <ets>lectaria</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>lectus</ets> couch, bed. See <er>Lie</er> to be prostrated, and cf.
<er>Coverlet</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A bed or stretcher so
arranged that a person, esp. a sick or wounded person, may be easily
carried in or upon it.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is a <qex>litter</qex> ready; lay him in 't.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Straw, hay, etc., scattered on a floor, as bedding
for animals to rest on; also, a covering of straw for plants.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To crouch in <qex>litter</qex> of your stable planks.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Take off the <qex>litter</qex> from your kernel beds.</q>
<rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Things lying scattered about in a manner indicating
slovenliness; scattered rubbish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Strephon, who found the room was void.⟦br⟧
Stole in, and took a strict survey⟦br⟧
Of all the <qex>litter</qex> as it lay.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Disorder or untidiness resulting from scattered
rubbish, or from thongs lying about uncared for; <as>as, a room in a
state of <ex>litter</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The young brought forth at one time, by a cat, dog,
sow or other multiparous animal, taken collectively. Also Fig.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A wolf came to a sow, and very kindly offered to take care of her
<qex>litter</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>D. Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Reflect upon that numerous <qex>litter</qex> of strange, senseless
opinions that crawl about the world.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Litter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Litter
<hw>Lit"ter</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Littered</conjf> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧t"t⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Littering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To supply
with litter, as cattle; to cover with litter, as the floor of a
stall.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tell them how they <qex>litter</qex> their jades.</q> <rj><qau>Bp.
Hackett.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For his ease, well <qex>littered</qex> was the floor.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To put into a confused or disordered condition; to
strew with scattered articles; <as>as, to <ex>litter</ex> a
room</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The room with volumes <qex>littered</qex> round.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To give birth to; to bear; -- said of brutes, esp.
those which produce more than one at a birth, and also of human beings,
in abhorrence or contempt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We might conceive that dogs were created blind, because we observe
they were <qex>littered</qex> so with us.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T.
Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The son that she did <qex>litter</qex> here,⟦br⟧
A freckled whelp hagborn.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 861 --></p>

<p><ent>Litter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Litter
<hw>Lit"ter</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧t"t⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To be supplied with litter as bedding; to sleep or make
one's bed in litter.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The inn⟦br⟧
Where he and his horse <qex>littered</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Habington.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To produce a litter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A desert . . . where the she-wolf still <qex>littered</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Litterateur</ent>⟦br⟧
